%N A087192 a(n) = ceiling(a(n-1)*4/3), with a(1) = 1.
%C A087192 If you repeatedly base 64 encode a string, starting with a single character, the length of the string at step n is 4*a(n). - _Christian Perfect_, Jan 06 2016
%C A087192 Conjecture: There is a constant k (with a value of about 1.557296798) such that, for all n, 0<k*(4/3)^n-a(n)<2. This conjecture has been verified for all n up to 10^6. - _Clive Tooth_, Dec 24 2025
%C A087192 From _Jianing Song_, Dec 28 2025: (Start)
%C A087192 The conjecture above is correct. In fact, the constant k is (3/4)*A390321.
%C A087192 In general, let {f_n}_{n>=0} be the sequence defined by f_{n+1} = alpha*f_n + e_n, where alpha > 1, a <= e_n <= b, then f_n = (f_0 + e_0/alpha + ... + e_{n-1}/alpha^n)*alpha^n = c*alpha^n - (e_n/alpha + e_{n+1}/alpha^2 + ...), where c = f_0 + Sum_{n>=0} e_n/alpha^{n+1}. We conclude that c*alpha^n - b/(alpha - 1) <= f_n <= c*alpha^n - a/(alpha - 1).
%C A087192 Here alpha = 4/3, a = 0, and b = 2/3, so we conclude that c*(4/3)^n - 2 < a(n+1) = f_n < c*(4/3)^n for some constant c, since we have neither e_n = 0 for all sufficiently large n nor e_n = 2/3 for all sufficiently large n. (End)
